Her children Beatie and Ben Edney said in a statement: “She has lived an amazing life and gave us joy and laughter right up to the end. Just yesterday we were reminiscing together about all our adventures.”  Sylvia went to the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art before TV roles led to film. In 1958, she played Sister Diana in the war film Ice Cold In Alex. In a famous finale scene, she, John Mills, Anthony Quayle and Harry Andrews finally enjoy a beer in an Alexandria pub. She also made the groundbreaking 1961 film Victim, portraying the wife of a barrister, played by Sir Dirk Bogarde, who is having a gay relationship. Homosexuality was illegal at the time. Sylvia’s other appearances included No Time for Tears (1957) and The Tamarind Seed (1974). More recently she played the Queen Mother opposite Dame Helen Mirren in 2006’s The Queen. The following year, she was awarded an OBE in the Queen’s Birthday Honours. Her TV work included EastEnders and Heartbeat. Her most recent role was as Mrs Rawson in BBC period drama Gentleman Jack in 2019. 